b"30 years ago today our founder, Gary Erickson, and his friend Jay embarked on a 175-mile bike ride in Northern California. This legendary ride later became known as the \xe2\x80\x9cEpiphany Ride\xe2\x80\x9d because it is where Gary first thought of the idea to create CLIF BAR. 

30 years later, we\xe2\x80\x99re still here. A family and employee-owned company with a mission to pump as much good into the world as possible. 

We\xe2\x80\x99d like to thank everyone who has supported us along the way and allowed us to achieve everything we have over these past 30 years. We couldn't have done it without you all. :red_heart_selector::red_heart_selector::red_heart_selector:

b'In February 2019 we launched the Second Responder Fund to support communities after natural disasters. 100% of the net profits from the sales of our Sierra Trail Mix CLIF BAR go into the fund. The fund\xe2\x80\x99s first recipient was @buttehumane to help them to build a new state-of-the-art shelter and clinic to care for the animals in the community impacted by the Camp Fire.\n.\nIn this episode of #RaisingTheBar we look back at the devastation of the Camp Fire and show the recent groundbreaking of @buttehumane\xe2\x80\x99s new shelter.'

b"Founded in San Rafael, California in 1988 by social activist & mountain biking pioneer Marilyn Price, @TripsforKidsNational is a national nonprofit that offers transformative cycling experience to kids between the ages of 10-17 with an emphasis for at-risk and underserved youth. They use a bicycle as a tool to instill self-confidence, personal responsibility, achievement and appreciation for the environment.
.
Over 230,000 young people have had positive experiences thanks to Trips for Kids since 1988. Their goal is to reach at least 10,000 youth annually through their vast network of chapters across North America.
.
The organization believes that all youth should have the opportunity to know the benefits a bicycle can provide them. They believe that together, we can change kids' lives, two wheels at a time.
.
To learn more about this amazing organization and how you can get involved or donate to their cause click the link in our bio."

b"At CLIF, we know firsthand the positive impact bikes can have in a person's life, which is why we are thrilled to be supporters of organizations like Chicago-based  @WestTownBikes
.
West Town Bikes empowers youth of all abilities and circumstances to build stronger, healthier communities. Respecting their diversity in culture, identity, and opinion, they develop creativity, self-sufficiency and economic opportunity through hands-on education and business development. As a youth development organization their programs use bikes as a tool for positive transformation.
.
To learn how you can get involved or donate to help their organization, click the link in our bio."

b'@bayareawildernesstraining is an organization that creates equitable access to outdoor experiences for youth of color and low-income youth.
.
BAWT achieves its mission by providing outdoor leadership trainings to teachers and youth workers, as well as maintains three gear libraries across the Bay Area\xe2\x80\x94in Oakland, San Francisco, and Milpitas. Upon completion of leadership training courses, course alumni have access to borrowing gear\xe2\x80\x94tents, sleeping bags, hiking boots, base layers, and more\xe2\x80\x94free of charge.
.
Learn more about this amazing organization and how you can either get involved or donate to their cause through the link in our bio.'

b'Youth from urban, under-resourced communities have long faced barriers to accessing and connecting with nature, which has negative implications for their health, vibrancy, and resilience. @campingtoconnect a program from the Young Masterminds Initiative, guides young men of color from New York City on journeys into the outdoors that offer fundamental camping and survival skills, leadership training, mentorship, an introduction to healthy living habits, and an opportunity for self-reflection and peer bonding. To learn more and support the work they are doing, check out the link in our bio'

b'At Clif Bar, we run our business based on 5 bottom lines. In honor of the 50th anniversary Earth Day we take a moment to reflect on how these aspirations have guided us to run a different kind of company. Take a look at some of the highlights from 2019. 
Sustaining our Planet
At our bakery in Idaho, we launched a 5-acre solar farm with pollinator habitat. 
Sustaining our People
We invested in a $10 million expansion at our bakery in Indiana that includes a fitness area, wellness room, and biophilic design. 
Sustaining our Community
At our annual CLIF CORPS Community Service Day, more than 350 Clif employees volunteered at 15 national parks, monuments, and historic sites across the U.S. and abroad. 
Sustaining our Brands
We released our new Coffee Collection made with fair trade, shade-grown, certified-organic coffee. 
Sustaining our Business
We sourced 143 million pounds of organic ingredients in 2019 -- that\xe2\x80\x99s more than 1.2 billion lbs. of ingredients grown without toxic persistent pesticides or synthetic fertilizers since 2003. 
Aerial photo by @jaredlauritsen'

b'We are deeply saddened by yesterday's loss of CLIF Athlete @zegermanbs (Ben Sonntag). Ben has been a part of the CLIF family for more than 10 years and has played an integral role within @clifproteam Ben will be greatly missed and our hearts go out to his family and friends. . "We are all absolutely heartbroken to let everyone know that we have lost a member of our family, Ben Sonntag. Our hearts and thoughts are with his family, teammates, friends, and fans as we all cope with this terrible tragedy.
.
Ben had been with CLIF Bar for more than 10 years and we can't tell you how saddened we are by this\xe2\x80\x94first and foremost for Ben and his immediate family\xe2\x80\x94but also for the entire cycling community as we bear another unspeakably senseless loss of life.
.
As cyclists, we put our lives at risk every time we strike out on the road, but somehow, we deem these risks acceptable as we practice our craft. Sadly, something like this brings those risks into focus and sheds a glaring light on the exposure we all have out there; exposure that increases daily with the proliferation of distractions from mobile phones and other devices. But this is what we do.
.
Please be careful out there and keep Ben and his family in your immediate thoughts.
.
Godspeed Ben. May you rest in peace." - Dave McLaughlin, CLIF BAR Pro Team Manager'

b"Ontario, Canada isn't necessarily known for its mountains but the terrain @bluemtnresort is an exception. Check out this weeks #CLIFMountainInsider from Blue Mountain local @MainGirlKeeks
.
\xe2\x80\x9cGrowing up in Ontario and loving winter means one thing, snowboarding at @BlueMtnResort Not only is it Ontario\xe2\x80\x99s largest ski resort but you can challenge yourself in the glades, send it in the park and embrace the power hour laps with friends. I grew up with @BlueMtnResort as my babysitter, and have some of my favourite memories growing up there. It\xe2\x80\x99 fun to be able to go back and share my knowledge with the next generation of riders and help them fall in love with the sport and place that captivated me. I love to pop into the glades and find the pockets of powder and then linking that line into the lower badlands. Getting to play in the park, explore the glades and send it with friends is why I keep coming back to Blue.\xe2\x80\x9d - @MainGirlKeeks

b'This week\xe2\x80\x99s #CLIFMountainInsider takes us to the legendary Western Territory at @snowshoemtn Learn more about the Mid-Atlantic\xe2\x80\x99s most challenging terrain below.
.
Descending 1,500 vertical feet from Snowshoe\xe2\x80\x99s mountaintop village, the Western Territory provides southern skiers and snowboarders with a big mountain experience without the flight west. Two twin black diamonds, Cupp Run and Shay\xe2\x80\x99s Revenge, run parallel for 1.5 miles to the valley floor.
.
Cupp Run was designed in the early 1970\xe2\x80\x99s by none other than Jean Claude-Killy, the world-renowned French ski racer. It is home to the Cupp Run Challenge, a giant slalom race that has been held annually on the first Monday in February since 1975. Shay\xe2\x80\x99s Revenge would come along years later, bringing with it the region\xe2\x80\x99s first double-black diamond ski slope on the lower section of the trail. Both trails are lined with a state-of-the-art snowmaking system.
.
A popular line choice for many Snowshoe regulars is to start off on the wide, meandering Upper Shay\xe2\x80\x99s Revenge before traversing over to the thrilling steep of Lower Cupp Run, with some excellent tree skiing in between via Sunset Glades when conditions allow. #FeedYourAdventure'

b"This weeks #CLIFMountainInsider is Steins Way @deervalleyresort learn more about this historic run below :down_arrow_selector:
.
Steins Way was one of the first ski runs cut when the resort opened in 1981 off Bald Mountain. It was named after the legendary Stein Eriksen, Olympic medalist and director of skiing at Deer Valley. It is a run perfectly suited for his classy, giant-slalom-style turns.
.
Steins Way begins at the top of the Sultan chairlift and winds down through some of the resort's most scenic areas with great views of Jordanelle Reservoir. It alternates between steep pitches, rolling inclines and gentle platforms perfect for wide, sweeping turns.
.
The run drops 1,300 vertical feet and is 4,500 feet long. Most of the run is intermediate, except for one pitch with a 70-degree slope, which is a double black diamond. Intermediate skiers can bypass the steep, ski around and ski back on the run where it returns to intermediate terrain."
